{ Die Sichtbarkeit eines LTevalRules bzgl. des Modulkontextes wird in RBTimeRelevantRule in LTstubs.pro }
{ ueberprueft.		2-Sept-1996 LWEB }

ded_Adot(_cc,_x,_y) :-
    ground(_cc),
    !,
    do_ded_Adot(_cc,_x,_y).


{* 20-Jan-2005/M.Jeusfeld: this case is redundant. If ded_Adot is called with *}
{* missing _cc (or _ml), then these parameters will be filled by unification  *}
{* with the rule heads of LTevalRule(_cc,Adot(_cc,_x,_y))                 *}
{* 16-Sep-2005/C.Quix: This case is necessary. Unification with rule heads    *}
{* means evaluating the rules, and as _cc and _ml are unbound, all rules will *}
{* be evaluated. Therefore, these additional cases bind _cc and _ml before    *}
{* calling prove_by_cache. We consider here only explicit instances of x resp.*}
{* y to avoid the evaluation of all In-rules. *}
{* 12-Oct-2005/M.Jeusfeld: We can't limit only to explicit instances. This    *}
{* prevents us from evaluation ded_Adot in case that x is an instance of some *}
{* class c by means of a rule and that class has an attribute cc. Note that   *}
{* attribute instantiation is generalized in ticket #61. In such cases, the   *}
{* old implementation of ded_Adot would not find derived solutions. With the  *}
{* change of today, we use any deductive rule that matches                    *}
{* Adot(_cc,_x,_y). By backtracking over the fast IS_DEDUCABLE, we take   *}
{* care of binding variables in/by rule heads as much as possible. We still   *}
{* rely on the assumption that _ml is bound. Hence, not any rule head will    *}
{* match.                                                                     *}
{* 1-Jun-2006/M.Jeusfeld: It can happen that ded_Adot is called with cc,x,y   *}
{* all being free variables. Such a call can happen from the procedure        *}
{* findInsertTriggerToFire when the literal in the save_setof clause has the  *}
{* form A(x,ml,y). Such calls need to be evaluated. We at least demand that ml*}
{* or x or y is ground. Calls with free ml occur via get_object with parameter*}
{* dedWith set to TRUE.                                                       *}

ded_Adot(_cc,_x,_y) :-
   (ground(_x);ground(_y)),
   !,
   IS_DEDUCABLE(Adot(_cc,_x,_y)),  {* if there is more than one rule head, we shall backtrack *}
   prove_by_cache(Adot(_cc,_x,_y)).



{* do_ded_Adot takes care of two cases:                                        *}
{*                                                                             *}
{* case 1: there is a rule that derived Adot(_cc,_x,_y)                        *}
{*                                                                             *}
{* case 2: there is a rule that derived Adot_label(_cc,_x,_y,_l)               *}
{*         this comes into play when the user formulates rules deriving        *}
{*         (x m/n y) instead (x m y)                                           *}

do_ded_Adot(_cc,_x,_y) :-
  prove_by_cache(Adot(_cc,_x,_y));
  prove_by_cache(Adot_label(_cc,_x,_y,_l)).




ded_Adot_label(_cc,_x,_y,_l) :-
    prove_by_cache(Adot_label(_cc,_x,_y,_l)).




{Instantiation to system classes Proposition,Individual,Attribute,InstanceOf,IsA:}

{* there used to be a check that made sure that _c is not a non-system class   *}
{* This guard_class check did however eat only CPU time instead of saving it.  *}
{* Probably, guard_class was useful when the object store was still realized   *}
{* in Prolog. The sysclass utility is now based on the C-based object store    *}
{* and that obviously is faster without the guard_class.                       *}

sys_In(_id,_c) :-
	sysclass(_id,_c).




